 ">full entry</a></span></span></span></div><div class="collapse" hclass="collapse" htag="div"><span class="unbox" id="aloof_unbox_1" unbox="wordorigin"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">mid 16th cent.: from <span class="ei">a-</span> (expressing direction) + <span class="ei">luff</span> ‘the edge of a type of sail next to the mast or stay’. The term was originally an adverb in nautical use, meaning ‘away and to windward!’, i.e. with the ship's head kept close to the wind away from a lee shore etc. towards which it might drift. From this arose the sense ‘at a distance’.</span></span></span></div>          <div id="ring-links-box">
